You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput Spring Boot application utilizing Java 21 Virtual Threads experiences severe performance degradation. Thread dumps reveal many virtual threads are in the `PINNED` state. The culprit code snippet looks like this:

java
@Service
public class LegacyDataService {
    private final Object lock = new Object();
    @Autowired
    private RestTemplate restTemplate;

    @Transactional
    public void processData(String id) {
        synchronized(lock) {
            // Blocking network call to legacy system
            restTemplate.getForObject("https://legacy-api/" + id, String.class);
        }
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where an API endpoint updates a user status and then sends an email confirmation asynchronously. The code is structured as follows:

java
@Service
public class UserService {
    @Autowired
    private UserRepository userRepository;
    @Autowired
    private EmailService emailService;

    @Transactional
    public void updateUserAndNotify(Long userId) {
        User user = userRepository.findById(userId).orElseThrow();
        user.setStatus(Status.ACTIVE);
        userRepository.save(user);

        CompletableFuture.runAsync(() -> {
            emailService.sendWelcomeEmail(userId);
        });
    } 
}

Under load, users complain that `emailService.sendWelcomeEmail` fails because it queries the database and finds the user status is still `PENDING` instead of `ACTIVE`.

You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput orchestration service experiences severe latency spikes and eventually crashes with an `OutOfMemoryError` (OOM: Java heap space). The service uses `CompletableFuture.supplyAsync()` heavily with a custom executor configured as follows:

java
@Bean
public Executor taskExecutor() {
    return new ThreadPoolExecutor(
        10, 100, 60L, TimeUnit.SECONDS,
        new LinkedBlockingQueue<Runnable>()
    );
}

Under peak load, tasks are accepted, but response times increase exponentially, and heap memory usage grows linearly until exhaustion.
